   1  # Agent
   2  
   3  A local, tool-driven coding assistant that talks to an OpenAI-compatible LLM endpoint (e.g. `llama-server` from `llama.cpp`) and runs an autonomous file/shell tool loop. It is built to survive long sessions: it checkpoints every turn, summarizes older history in the background, recovers from malformed tool calls, and catches common hallucinations before they poison context.
   4  
   5  ## Quick start
   6  
   7  1. Start an OpenAI-compatible LLM server locally. The default endpoint is `http://127.0.0.1:8080`:
   8  
   9     ```bash
  10     llama-server -m your-model.gguf --port 8080
  11     ```
  12  
  13  2. (Optional) create a `config.json` in your working directory to override defaults — see [Configuration](#configuration).
  14  
  15  3. Run the agent:
  16  
  17     ```bash
  18     python agent.py "fix the failing test in tests/test_parser.py"
  19     ```
  20  
  21  ## CLI
  22  
  23  ```
  24  python agent.py [OPTIONS] [PROMPT...]
  25  ```
  26  
  27  | Flag | Description |
  28  | --- | --- |
  29  | `-a`, `--auto` | Automation mode — run the prompt and exit; no interactive loop. |
  30  | `-c`, `--continue` | Resume from the last checkpoint (picks up a crashed or interrupted cycle). |
  31  | `-r N`, `--repeat N` | Run the prompt `N` times with fresh state each run. `0` or omitted means run indefinitely. Implies `-a`. |
  32  | `--nudge` | When the model returns a text-only response (no tool calls), auto-nudge it to keep going instead of stopping. Off by default. |
  33  | `PROMPT...` | Initial prompt. Optional; in interactive mode you'll be prompted if omitted. |
  34  
  35  Press **Escape twice** within 400ms to cancel a streaming response.
  36  
  37  ### Interactive commands
  38  
  39  In the interactive loop, lines starting with `/` are commands:
  40  
  41  | Command | Description |
  42  | --- | --- |
  43  | `/help` | List available commands. |
  44  | `/clear` | Clear conversation history and start a fresh session log. |
  45  | `/context` | Show current context usage as an Aurora-gradient bar with token counts. |
  46  | `/model` | Pick a different model from the server's `/v1/models` endpoint (summarizer keeps its original). |
  47  | `exit` / `quit` | End the session. |
  48  
  49  ### Colors
  50  
  51  The terminal UI uses the **Aurora** palette (violet → sky → mint) via `theme.py`. `NO_COLOR=1` or piping to a file disables all colors and cursor escapes automatically.
  52  
  53  ## How it works
  54  
  55  Each cycle is a turn loop:
  56  
  57  1. Build a context window from recent history plus an async summary of older history.
  58  2. Stream a response from the LLM.
  59  3. Execute any tool calls.
  60  4. Feed results back in and repeat until the model stops calling tools, a cycle limit is hit, or the user cancels.
  61  
  62  The loop has a few guardrails worth knowing about:
  63  
  64  - **Checkpointing.** Conversation history and summary state are written to `.agent/state/conversation_checkpoint.json` every turn. `--continue` resumes from there.
  65  - **Async summarization.** If a summary endpoint is configured, a background thread condenses older messages while the main model keeps working. The summary is swapped in when ready.
  66  - **Cycle limits & wind-down.** After `cycle.max_turns` turns (default 100), the agent is asked to wrap up; after `cycle.wind_down_turns` more turns it is forced to stop.
  67  - **Text-loop detection.** If the model emits the same text three times in a row, the cycle ends instead of looping forever.
  68  - **Hallucination guards.** When the model claims to have read a file it never actually read, the fabricated message is stripped and a correction injected. Malformed tool-call JSON is also salvaged heuristically.
  69  - **Tool recovery.** When a tool fails with a recognizable error (e.g. bad line numbers), `tool_recovery.py` tries to re-run it with corrected parameters via a lightweight LLM call.
  70  - **Context overflow handling.** Three consecutive HTTP 500s from the LLM endpoint are treated as context overflow — the agent trims history and retries.
  71  
  72  ## Project layout
  73  
  74  ```
  75  agent.py            # Main loop, streaming, context management, checkpointing
  76  cancel.py           # Double-escape cancel handler
  77  spinner.py          # Aurora-pulsed waiting/streaming/done visual feedback
  78  theme.py            # Aurora color palette + single source of ANSI escapes
  79  token_utils.py      # Tokenizer (Gemma) with char-based fallback
  80  tool_recovery.py    # Auto-recovery from recoverable tool errors
  81  tools/              # Built-in tools (see below)
  82    file.py           # read / write / insert / append / delete / list
  83    exec_command.py   # Shell execution with background-session support
  84    search_files.py   # Grep-like search with glob and case controls
  85    read_pdf.py       # PDF text extraction (PyMuPDF)
  86    web_fetch.py      # URL → markdown, saved to disk with inline preview
  87    think.py          # Deep-reasoning tool via a separate thinking call
  88    task_tracker.py   # Persistent task list in .agent/state/tasks.json
  89    sleep.py          # Pause execution
  90  .agent/             # Runtime artifacts (created on first run, gitignored)
  91    state/
  92      conversation_checkpoint.json
  93      tasks.json
  94      current-state.json
  95      cycle.txt
  96      fetched/        # Cached web_fetch output
  97    history/
  98      session-*.log   # Per-session verbose logs
  99  ```
 100  
 101  Agent-specific tools can also live in `./tools/` alongside your working directory — they are auto-discovered and registered on startup.
 102  
 103  ## Configuration
 104  
 105  Drop a `config.json` in the working directory to override any of the built-in defaults. The top-level sections are:
 106  
 107  - **`llm`** — `base_url`, `model`. The OpenAI-compatible endpoint and model name.
 108  - **`generation`** — `temperature`, `top_p`, `top_k`, `presence_penalty`.
 109  - **`context`** — `ctx_size`, `max_tokens`, `max_full_lines`, `preview_lines`, `summary_threshold`, `summary_max_chars`, `max_context_messages`. Controls how history is sized and when it gets summarized.
 110  - **`cycle`** — `max_turns`, `wind_down_turns`, `max_text_only`. Per-cycle turn budget and text-only nudge cap.
 111  - **`retry`** — `max_retries`, `base_delay_seconds`, `max_delay_seconds`, `backoff_multiplier`, `jitter_factor`. Exponential backoff for transient LLM errors.
 112  - **`summary`** — `enabled`, `base_url`, `model`, `max_wait_on_save`. Optional separate summarization endpoint (default port 8082).
 113  
 114  Example minimal override:
 115  
 116  ```json
 117  {
 118    "llm": { "base_url": "http://127.0.0.1:8080", "model": "gemma-4-31B" },
 119    "context": { "ctx_size": 32768 },
 120    "cycle": { "max_turns": 50 }
 121  }
 122  ```
 123  
 124  ## Dependencies
 125  
 126  - Python 3.7+
 127  - `requests` — HTTP to the LLM endpoint
 128  - `transformers` + `torch` — Gemma tokenizer (optional; falls back to a character-based estimate if missing)
 129  - `PyMuPDF` (`fitz`) — PDF extraction, used by `tools/read_pdf.py`
 130  - `markdownify` — HTML → Markdown conversion, used by `tools/web_fetch.py`
 131  - A running OpenAI-compatible LLM server (e.g. `llama-server`)
 132  - Bash, and a TTY for the cancel handler
 133  
 134  ## State and logs
 135  
 136  Everything runtime lives under `.agent/` in the working directory:
 137  
 138  - `.agent/state/conversation_checkpoint.json` — last checkpoint for `--continue`
 139  - `.agent/state/tasks.json` — persistent task list used by the `task_tracker` tool
 140  - `.agent/state/current-state.json` — per-cycle scratch state
 141  - `.agent/state/cycle.txt` — monotonic cycle counter
 142  - `.agent/state/fetched/` — cached `web_fetch` downloads
 143  - `.agent/history/session-*.log` — verbose per-session logs
 144  
 145  Delete the `.agent/` directory to start completely fresh. The whole tree is gitignored.

